<b>Causes</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">The WHO states, â€œSevere measles is more likely among poorly nourished young children, especially those with insufficient vitamin A, or whose immune systems have been weakened by HIV/AIDS or other diseases. The most serious complications include blindness, encephalitis (an infection that causes brain swelling), severe diarrhoea and related dehydration, and severe respiratory infections such as pneumonia."</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">This is a highly contagious infection caused by a virus. A weak immune system is the one-point cause of the infection. The virus remains active for 2 hours on any object. It spreads through:</span>
<ul>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â </span> <span style="font-weight: 400;">Contact with an infected person.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Inhaling the sneeze or cough droplets of someone with an infection.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â </span> <span style="font-weight: 400;">Smoking near an infected person could make it worse for the person. </span></li>
</ul>
<b>Treatments</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Unless you have developed another health condition because of measles, your doctor will not give you any medication. Dehydration, is the most common ailment that occurs as a result of measles. Therefore, having plenty of healthy fluids and water is your first line of defense against the illness. </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Cough medicines and medicines to treat the underlying causes could be extremely helpful too. Vitamin A supplements are commonly given to someone who suffers from such an infection.</span>";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"0";}}